<DocsLayout title="Docker & Experiments" toc={toc}>

  <h1>Docker & Experiments</h1>

  <p>
    Docker is mandatory for all experiments on AIRLab servers. It is not optional, and
    it is not just for production code. Running experiments inside containers ensures
    that every result is reproducible — by you six months from now, by your co-supervisor,
    and by any future lab member who builds on your work.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Why Docker ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="why">Why Docker?</h2>

  <p>
    Without containers, every researcher installs packages globally with <code>pip</code>
    or <code>conda</code>. Over time, incompatible versions accumulate, experiments break,
    and nobody can tell which version of a library produced which result. Docker fixes this:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Isolation</strong> — your dependencies cannot interfere with anyone else's, and vice versa.</li>
    <li><strong>Reproducibility</strong> — pin every dependency to an exact version; anyone can rebuild the same environment from scratch.</li>
    <li><strong>Portability</strong> — the same container runs on Westworld, a cloud VM, or your laptop (CPU-only).</li>
    <li><strong>Clean servers</strong> — no global package pollution; the server OS stays pristine.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ── Project Structure ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="structure">Project Structure</h2>

  <p>
    Every project should follow this layout. It makes your repository self-contained —
    anyone who clones it can build the environment and run the code without asking you
    anything.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="text"
    filename="my_project/"
    code={`my_project/
├── src/                   # your source code
│   ├── train.py
│   ├── evaluate.py
│   └── models/
├── configs/               # YAML/JSON configuration files
│   └── default.yaml
├── Dockerfile             # image definition
├── requirements.txt       # Python dependencies (pinned versions)
├── .runconfig             # dataset mounts, GPU allocation, env vars
├── .gitignore
└── README.md              # setup & usage instructions`}
  />

  <!-- ── Dockerfile ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="dockerfile">Writing a Dockerfile</h2>

  <p>
    Start from an official NVIDIA base image that bundles CUDA and cuDNN. Pick the
    version that matches the CUDA toolkit installed on Westworld (ask your co-supervisor
    or run <code>nvidia-smi</code> and check the top-right CUDA version).
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="dockerfile"
    filename="Dockerfile"
    code={`# ── Base image ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Replace with the CUDA version that matches Westworld.
# Browse available tags at: https://hub.docker.com/r/nvidia/cuda/tags
FROM nvidia/cuda:12.1.0-cudnn8-runtime-ubuntu22.04

# ── System dependencies ───────────────────────────────────
# Install only what is truly needed; keep layers small.
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
      python3.11 \
      python3.11-venv \
      python3-pip \
      git \
      libgl1 \
      libglib2.0-0 \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

# ── Python environment ────────────────────────────────────
WORKDIR /workspace
COPY requirements.txt .

RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --upgrade pip \
    && pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

# ── Project code ──────────────────────────────────────────
COPY src/ ./src/
COPY configs/ ./configs/

# Default command (override at runtime)
CMD ["python3", "src/train.py"]`}
  />

  <p>
    Pin every dependency to an exact version in <code>requirements.txt</code>. Use
    <code>pip freeze</code> in a working environment to generate the list, or specify
    versions manually:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="text"
    filename="requirements.txt"
    code={`torch==2.2.1+cu121
torchvision==0.17.1+cu121
torchaudio==2.2.1+cu121
--extra-index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu121

numpy==1.26.4
opencv-python-headless==4.9.0.80
matplotlib==3.8.4
tqdm==4.66.2
pyyaml==6.0.1
tensorboard==2.16.2`}
  />

  <!-- ── Building ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="building">Building Images</h2>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld — project root"
    code={`# Build the image. Convention: <username>/<project>:<version>
docker build --rm -t lastname/my_project:v1 .

# Verify the image was built
docker images | grep my_project

# Remove dangling images (untagged build cache)
docker image prune`}
  />

  <p>
    The <code>--rm</code> flag removes intermediate containers after the build completes,
    keeping the server tidy. Rebuild after any change to your <code>Dockerfile</code> or
    <code>requirements.txt</code>.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Running ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="running">Running Containers</h2>

  <p>
    AIRLab servers provide a helper script called <code>run-docker</code> that wraps
    the standard <code>docker run</code> command with sensible defaults (GPU assignment,
    current-directory mount, user permissions). Ask your co-supervisor how to obtain it.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld"
    code={`# Usage: run-docker <gpu_indices> <cpu_cores> <command...>
# Example: use GPU 0, 4 CPU cores, run training
run-docker 0 4 python3 src/train.py --config configs/default.yaml

# Use two GPUs (0 and 1), 8 cores
run-docker 0,1 8 python3 src/train_multi_gpu.py

# Start an interactive bash shell inside the container (useful for debugging)
run-docker 0 4 bash`}
  />

  <p>
    If <code>run-docker</code> is not yet available, here is the equivalent raw Docker command:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    code={`docker run --rm --gpus '"device=0"' \
  --cpuset-cpus="0-3" \
  -v "$(pwd)":/workspace \
  -w /workspace \
  --user "$(id -u):$(id -g)" \
  lastname/my_project:v1 \
  python3 src/train.py`}
  />

  <!-- ── Run Configs ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="runconfigs">Run Configurations (.runconfig)</h2>

  <p>
    The <code>.runconfig</code> file lets you declare persistent options for
    <code>run-docker</code> without repeating them on the command line every time.
    Common uses: mounting dataset directories, exposing ports, and setting environment
    variables.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename=".runconfig"
    code={`# Mount your private dataset directory into the container
-v ~/datasets/private/coco:/data/coco:ro

# Mount a shared lab dataset (read-only)
-v /data/shared/imagenet:/data/imagenet:ro

# Expose a port (e.g., for TensorBoard)
-p 6006:6006

# Set environment variables
-e WANDB_API_KEY=your_key_here
-e PYTHONPATH=/workspace/src`}
  />

  <!-- ── Jupyter ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="jupyter">Jupyter Notebooks</h2>

  <p>
    Notebooks are useful for exploration and visualisation, but should not contain
    core training logic (see the <a href="/docs/git#notebooks">Git guide</a> for why).
    To run a Jupyter server inside a container:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld"
    code={`# Start Jupyter inside the container, exposed on port 8888
run-docker 0 4 jupyter notebook --ip=0.0.0.0 --port=8888 --no-browser`}
  />

  <p>
    Then, on your local machine, forward the port through SSH to access the notebook
    in your browser:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="local machine"
    code={`# Forward remote port 8888 to your local port 8888
ssh -L 8888:localhost:8888 airlab

# Open in your browser:
# http://localhost:8888
# (copy the token from the Jupyter output on the server)`}
  />

  <!-- ── Best Practices ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="best-practices">Best Practices</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Do</th><th>Don't</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Pin all dependency versions in <code>requirements.txt</code></td>
        <td>Use <code>pip install torch</code> (no version pin)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Use <code>--no-cache-dir</code> in <code>pip install</code></td>
        <td>Let pip cache accumulate inside the image layer</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Chain <code>RUN</code> commands with <code>&amp;&amp;</code> to reduce layers</td>
        <td>Create a separate <code>RUN</code> for each <code>apt-get install</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Tag images with meaningful version strings (<code>:v2</code>, <code>:exp-aug24</code>)</td>
        <td>Always use <code>:latest</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Mount datasets from outside the container (<code>-v</code>)</td>
        <td>Copy large datasets into the image with <code>COPY</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Run <code>docker image prune</code> periodically</td>
        <td>Let stale images accumulate and fill the server disk</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

</DocsLayout>
